	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">In some case, even if the game doesn't support multi-core, windows will try to spread the load on all of them so I guess there is not much you can do at the moment.</div>
<br />Too bad this default behavior breaks some games and older applications. I have to manually set CPU affinity to one core in Psychonauts or else I get glitched loading screens. Various other programs (usually 9x-era) will either behave strangely or crash.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
